spanGrp.span: when I was a little boy
I used to live with my grandmother
hakaraicisunu --> hakicisunu would be more correct (BO)
hegu Hoocak hitera hegu kiiraniisge naaxgusunu
all I used to hear was Hoocak talk
hegu Hocak hit'era hegu kiranisge naxgusunu
so hegu eeja yaatete hajitegaja hegu Hoocaki hegu kiiraniisge yaatetesununa
and when I started talking, Hoocak was about the only way I used to talk
so hegu 'eeja yaat'et'e hajitegaja hegu Hocagihegu kiraniisge yaat'et'esununa
hegu hoisip hegu Hoocak waaksik xeteirera ee waacawisunu
we always used to see the Hoocak elders
hegu hoisip hegu Hocak waaksik xetera ('ee) wacawisunu
haciija haciija hahiwigi zeegu kiiraniisge hacawisunu Hoocakgi zeegu kiira
wherever we went, that was the only thing we would see: the Hoocak
haciija haciija hahiwigi zeegu kiranisge hacawisunu Hocakig zeegu kira
hagoreiza heesge hegu Hoocakra hegu kiiraniisge naaxgusunu
one time Hoocak was all I heard
hagoreiza heesge hegu Hocagra hegu kiranisge naaxgusunu
also my parents were like that
hegu huukarakitairegizi Hoocak hegu kiiraniisge hitatairesunu
when they talked to me, they would only speak Hoocak
hegu hokarakit'airegizi Hocak hegu kiraniisge hit'at'airesunu
hikorooke haara hakarakikizu hegu hainixjiik yaakiwisunu
my grandmother and I used to wake up early in the morning
hegu haini_wooruc keeni wiira haaksiniisge jinakizi; zige
we had breakfast before the sun got up high, and..
hegu haini woruc keeni wiira haksiniisge jinakizi; zige
hikorookeik haarasge hegu ciira eegi piikarauanaga zige hegu jaagu woorera higiregi zeesge nunige niikjakiki waauajegaja hegu
my grandmother also took care of the house, and whatever her job or work was, she used to take good care of the house, but I myself was a child
hikorokeik haarasge hegu ciira 'eegi piikara'uanaga zige hegu jaagu woorera higiregi zeesge nunige nikjaigi wa'uaje(gaja hegu)

jaagu woorera higiregi = whatever his work was ; worera higireregi =whatever their work was higire = his / her ; higire = my ; hinigire = yours ; hinigirewi = yours (PL) higiregi = that belonged to her woore ze'e higirera/gi = that's my job, woore hanina = my job JH sollte so lauten: CW/CL pi\i-kara-k'u;
hegu caak eeja hasgac hegu nee hegu jaaguxjiniisge haukjenegi hegu eesgesge haasunu
I played outside, whatever I was going to do/whatever I wanted to do I used to do it
hegu caag 'eeja hasgac hegu nee jaaguxjinisge ha'ukjanegi (hegu) 'eesgesge haasunu
"hegu" missing after "nee"? -- LP: I think so, added on tx and mo.
zee hegu hagaira zige eegi ciinak eeja eeja hahiwisunu
once in a while we'd to go to town
zee hegu hagaira zige 'eegi ciinak 'eeja 'eeja hahiwisunu
eeja eeja waza hikorooke haara hegu roogugizi hegu heesge kiiruwianaga eegi hegu ciinak wooruwi_hoci eeja hegu
whatever my grandmother wanted she used to buy there, in the store
'eeja 'eeja waza hikoroke haara hegu roogugizi (hegu) heesge kiruwi(anaga) 'eegi hegu ciinak woroc 'eeja hegu
haariniisge hegu hakesge wazatireiza haniwini hegu moowe hahiwisunu
it was kind of far, we didn't have a car so we used to walk over
harinisge hegu hakesge wazatireiza hainiwini hegu mo'e hahiwisunu
mo'e = all messed up moowe = walk on the ground, walk by foot ; lit. to travel the ground (BO)
so hegu eeja wooruwi_hoci eeja hahikjanawigizi hainixji hegu wahac tuusjawigizi
early in the morning when we'd finished eating, we went to the store
so hegu 'eeja woroc 'eeja hahikjanawigizi hainixji hegu wahactusjawigizi
eegi hirusja hakiwi anaga eegi wooruwi_hoci eeja howateewisunu
when we were ready we used to go to the store we'd prepare ourselves and then go to the store
hegu hegu hija hahiwigizi eegi eegi waza_wahiiniisge eegi
when we got there, there some sort of relatives
hegu hegu hija hahiwigizi 'eegi 'eegi waza wahi hiisge 'eegi
wazawahi = his /her relatives wazawaraga = your relatives waza wahara = my realtives waza wahirera = their relatives
(ciinaik) ciinak xunuik niisge eeja ciiresunu eeja
they used to live in a real small town
"'eeja" missing at the end? -- LP: Yes, added on tx
hagaira eeja hahiwianaga hakocakniisge woomakini hahiwisunu anaga
we went over there sometimes, we used to visit them
eegi eegi eegi hagaira hake wazara roohaxjini eegi
sometimes there are not too many things here
hake woorera herenigizi eeja hikorooke haara hegu hegu hoogisik gipisunu
if there wasn't too much work around the house, my grandmother used to like to go fishing
woogera herenakgizi 'eeja hikoroke haara hegu hegu hogisik gipisunu
that's where we used to go fishing
hogisik hahiwisunu --> hoo haisik hahiiwisunu would be the proper way of saying this (BO)
nunige zige hegu haasikra eegi hagaira eeja waagihiwisunu
once in a while we'd pick little berries there sometimes
nunige zige hegu haasigra 'eegi hagaira 'eeja wagihiwisunu
it used to be enjoyable those were fine times
hegu haapserec niisge eesgesge haawi hegu hoohaisikwi anaga hegu
that's what we used to do all day long when we went fishing
hegu haapserec nisge 'eesgesge hawi hegu hohaisigi anaga hegu
zige haastik hagihiwigizi eegi haapserec niisge hauwisunu hige
it took us all day to pick blueberries when we picked blueberries, we'd do that all day long
zige haastik hagihiwigizi 'eegi haapserec niisge ha'uwisunu hige
there were a lot of us, but we used to live alone a lot of us lived there alone
hegu hagaira zige eeja saak wahaara haciija ciinaak gizi eeja hakocakik niisge eeja eeja haakjaniisge eeja hahiwi anaga eeja
once in a while, where my parents used to live, sometimes for a little while we used to go over there and back
hegu hagaire zige 'eeja s'aag wahara haciija ciinak gizi 'eeja hakocakik niisge 'eeja 'eeja haakjanisge 'eeja hahiwi anaga
hegu niikjak xununiisge hanihanaka hegu eeja Hoocak hegu kiiraniisge wooroohara yaaperessunu
I was a child then, there were only Hoocak I used to know alot of them
hegu nikja xununiisge hani hanaka (hegu 'eeja) Hocak hegu kiraniisge woora haniyaaperes sunu
when I was a child there were a lot of them
Hoocaknaakre hegu kiira Hoocak hegu kiira hitatairesunu
these Hoocak they only used to speak Hoocak
Hocaknaagre hegu kira Hocak kira hit'at'airesunu
eesge eeja maixete hitairesunu nunige wooroohara hegu Hoocak hitatairesunu
some of them spoke English but most of them that used to talk Hoocak
'eesge 'eeja maixete hit'airesunu nunige wooro haana hegu Hocak hit'at'airesunu
hegu nunige saak hiyahiiwira saak Hoocak saaknaakre hegu waaksik xete ciinakre eeja heesgesge hegu Hoocak hitera hegu kiiraniisge eegi
but our elders, the Hoocak elders, the real old people (in these houses) they only used to talk Hoocak
hegu nunige s'aag hiwahira s'aak Hocak s'aagnaagre hegu waaksik xete ciinagre 'eeja hesgesge hegu Hocak hit'era hegu kiraniisge 'eegi
they used to enjoy it they used to like that
nunige hegu waagaxhaja hajitegaja eeja hiraicera eegi maixete yaatera
but when I started to go to school, I talked more English there
nunige hegu wagaxraja hajitegaja 'eeja hiraicera 'eegi maixete yaat'egaja
yaate anaga hegu Hoocakra hegu hakocakniisge haakregi hakarakanaknaga
I talked and then I put Hoocak behind me for a while
yaat'e anaga hegu Hocagra hegu hakocakniisge haakregi hakaraknaknagra
hegu nunige cii eeja hagigizi naanieera hiuni haara hegu Hoocak hitataanaga hegu eegi hiac haara zige Hoocak hitataanaga hegu
but when I went back to the house my mother used to speak Hoocak and my father he used to speak Hoocak
hegu nunige cii 'eeja hagigizi nanieera hi'uni haara hegu Hocak hit'at'anaga hegu 'eegi hi'ac haara 'eeja Hocak hit'at'anaga hegu
zige hikorookeik haara hegu hakaraisjaga hegu hegu hegu Hoocak hegu hegu kiiraniisge huukarakitesunu
also when I used to go to my grandmother she used to talk to me in Hoocak
hige hikorokeik haara hegu hakaraisja hegu hegu hegu Hocak hegu hegu kiraniisge hukarakit'esunu
zige haciija hahiwigizi haciija Hoocakra eeja hostoiregizi eeja hegu wanaaraxgugizi hegu Hoocakra hitete hegu kiiraniisge
wherever we went, wherever the Hoocaks gathered, an if you listened to them there, they'd speak Hoocak only
zige hacija huwigizi hacija 'eeja Hocagra hostoiregizi 'eeja heegu wananaxgugizi hegu Hocagra hit'et'e (hegu) kiraniisge
they used to say, and it was a nice time
hegu hegu nunige saak hiyahiire heesge hiperesiregaja hegu
this is what our elders know
heegu hegu nunige s'aak hiwahiire heesge hipereshiregaja
"heegu" added at the end - LP: Ok.
hegu tee waaksgajaane eegi waza eegi eegi maa tee eegi eegi hijahiniisge hiirekjene
this white men they were going to make this land different
hegu tee waaksgajane 'eegi waza 'eegi 'eegi maa tee 'eegi 'eegi hija hinisge hirekjane
hegu eeja waagax eeja hiac haara eesgesge hiikaragawi anaga
and there, the school..... my father told us
hegu 'eeja wagax 'eeja hiac haara eesgesgi hikaragi anaga
eegi waagax_hajara eegi wasawasakikjawi heesgena hiikaragawi
in school you have to buckle down, that's what he told us you have to work had at school, he told us
'eegi wagax hajara 'eegi wasawa sagikjawi heesgena hikaragawi
wasawasagikjawi = you have to apply yourself to it wawasak =he... ; keep busy, apply oneself to, etc.
we have to do good there
that's all you have to do
hegu kira raakje heesge = that's all you have to do (BO)
if you do that you'll be all right in the future you'll be good / live good+
hake waagax_hasja waagax_hajara hake piiraanigizi eegi woceexi hasurusikjene

if you don't go to school, if you don't do good, it's not going to be very pleasant for you if you don't do well at school, you're going to go through bad times woocexi hasurusikjane you're gonna have a difficult time
hake wagax hasja wagax hajara ke piiranigizi woocexi hasurusikjane

(nigi) added by BO ft: if you don't go to school, if you don't do good in school; you're gonna have a bad time woocexi harusikjane = 3SG harus = that's what (s)he's gonna get
hiac haara heesge hiperes zige hiuni haara heesge hiperes naga
my father and my mother knew that
hi'ac haara heesge hiperes zige hi'uni haara hesge hiperes
hegu hojisanaik hihanakaja hegu hakocakniisge Hoocak hoitera haakregi hakarakanaknaga
as I was saying a little while ago, for a little while, the Hoocak language, I put it away
hegu hojisanaik hihanakgra (hegu) hikanakgaja Hocak hoit'era haagregi hakarakanak
hikanakgaja = when he married me (woman talking) hakanakgaja = when I married her
hegu yaaregaja hegu keeni siini hake eeja Hoocak hoitera eeja eegi yaakarakuni anaga eegi coowesge xawani hakaraginak.
I thought about it; not long after I didn't use the Hoocak language and I almost lost it
hegu yaaregaja hegu ke wis'ini ke 'eeja Hocak hoit'era ('eeja) 'eegi hake yakarak'uni anaga ('eegi) cowesge xawani hakaragigianak
can't hear "hake" before "yakarak'uni" -- LP: Deleted on tx and mo.
hakaragi(gi)naana --> second gi is not correct cowesge = just.about ; pretty close (BO) hakaragi = mine ; karagi = his own ; rakaragi = your own karagiire = theirs
eegi nunige hiac haara hoisip heesgesge hiikaragesununa eegi hirakiicgakje heesge
that's what my father used to always tell me "you have to practice it"
'eegi nunige hi'ac haara hoisip heesge(sge) hikaragesununa hirakicgakje heesge
that's the way it is with the mind and my thoughts
wowewi = thinking ; what you think with ; doesn't mean "mind"! (BO)

I was that way I'm doing that

we used to live in white hill, when I was ready to come back they left me
hit'unenahire = they (tried to left me behind) t'une = 3sg leaves 3sg behind

and today I'm groping for words that's what I'm doing here, I cannot speak like my father used to speak the Hoocak language
